<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="105" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1184]" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,908,933]" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">Remarks</emphasis>
. The new species is somewhat similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Liu &amp; Yang" authorityName="Liu &amp; Yang" box="[779,1055,908,933]" class="Insecta" family="Chloropidae" genus="Centorisoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="105" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scutatum">
<emphasis box="[779,913,908,932]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">C. scutatum</emphasis>
Liu &amp; Yang
</taxonomicName>
in having the gena yellow except posterior 
<number box="[260,270,944,968]" pageId="4" pageNumber="105" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number box="[280,295,944,968]" pageId="4" pageNumber="105" value="2.0">2</number>
black, the legs yellow except for apical half of fore tibia and fore tarsus brown and the postgonite without minute serrations on inner margin near basiphallus. It can be separated from the latter by the following features: postpedicel yellow except distal 
<number box="[624,634,1016,1040]" pageId="4" pageNumber="105" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number box="[644,660,1016,1040]" pageId="4" pageNumber="105" value="4.0">4</number>
black, 
<number box="[744,779,1015,1040]" pageId="4" pageNumber="105" value="1.5">1.5</number>
times as long as its basal breadth; cercus nearly quadrate. In 
<taxonomicName box="[180,313,1052,1076]" class="Insecta" family="Chloropidae" genus="Centorisoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="105" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scutatum">
<emphasis box="[180,313,1052,1076]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">C. scutatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the postpedicel is yellowish brown except distal 
<number box="[867,877,1052,1076]" pageId="4" pageNumber="105" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number box="[887,902,1052,1076]" pageId="4" pageNumber="105" value="2.0">2</number>
black, 
<number box="[983,1018,1052,1076]" pageId="4" pageNumber="105" value="1.8">1.8</number>
times as long as its basal breadth; the cercus is scutelliform (
<bibRefCitation author="Liu" box="[405,607,1087,1112]" pageId="4" pageNumber="105" refString="Liu, X. Y. &amp; Yang, D. (2012) The genus Centorisoma Becker in China, with a key to world species (Diptera, Chloropidae). Zootaxa, 3361, 18 - 32." type="journal article" year="2012">
Liu &amp; Yang 
<number box="[546,607,1088,1112]" pageId="4" pageNumber="105" value="2012.0">2012</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="105" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1184]" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,326,1124,1149]" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">Etymology</emphasis>
. The specific name is from the Latin 
<emphasis box="[746,849,1125,1148]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">convexus</emphasis>
(“convex”), refers to the apical margin of the cercus being round.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
